"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/842"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28918"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97823"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man attends his general practice for a routine follow-up. His medical history includes recent onset of hypertension and type 2 diabetes for which he takes perindopril and metformin. He also has a long history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. His heartburn symptoms have been reasonably well controlled with esomeprazole, but recently he has become anxious as he is sometimes waking up at night with regurgitation. These symptoms have begun to interfere with his lifestyle as he sometimes feels food sticking in his oesophagus. He has been putting on weight recently and he wonders if this might be something to do with it. His blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg and pulse 84/min. His BMI is 28. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. The patient asks if he needs any tests done for his heartburn.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"The presence of which one of the following would be most suggestive of the need for further investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anxiety","Symptoms interfering with lifestyle","Increasing weight","Recent onset of dysphagia","Regurgitation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of \u0027red flag\u0027 symptoms in gastro-oesophageal reflux that indicate the need for investigation. These include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eunintentional weight loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Evomiting blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Edysphagia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esymptoms of anaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eage over 45 with long-standing reflux symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erecent onset of reflux symptoms in an elderly patient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eobesity with weekly reflux symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ewheezing or a cough\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of any one of these should prompt the practitioner to arrange an endoscopic examination of the upper digestive tract. The most sinister of these symptoms would be \u003Cstrong\u003Edysphagia\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst a peptic stricture used to be a relatively common complication of long-standing gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, with use of proton-pump inhibitors and good acid control, the more worrying cause of dysphagia to consider must be malignancy. While most of the symptoms in the list might be due to no more than a worsening of the reflux, the recent onset of such symptoms must alert the clinician to other, possibly serious, explanations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith regards to the alternative symptoms provided in the question, none of them are absolute indications for further investigation, but depending on their severity or how much they bother the patient, the doctor might consider further (endoscopic) assessment, if only to gauge the severity of the reflux.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysphagia in a patient with gastro-oesophageal reflux requires further investigation"],"references":["Bredenoord AJ, Pandolfino JE, Smout AJPM. Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Lancet. 2013 Jun 1;381(9881):1933-42.","Fass R. Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease. N Engl J Med 2022; 387:1207-16."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80378"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T16:34:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T16:34:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97823"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":